name: Civilian War Memorial
address: War Memorial Park, Bras Basah Road & Beach Road intersection, Singapore 189701
desc: Erected to remember the shared experiences and struggles of the major of races during World War II, the Civilian War Memorial is dedicated to all those who perished during the Japanese Occupation of Singapore between 15 February 1942 and 12 September 1945.

name: Republic of Singapore Navy Museum
desc: Tracing the development of naval forces in Singapore from the Straits Settlements Royal Voluntary Reserce to today's Republic of Singapore Navy,

name: Marina Wakeboarding Hub
address:
600 Ponggol Seventeenth Avenue 
Marina Country Club
Singapore 829734
desc: Houses numerous wakeboarding schools with a stable of instructors as well as 45 wakeboarding boats.

name: Orchidville
desc: Filled with landscaped gardens and beautiful orchids, Orchidville is the largest orchid farm in Singapore, occupying 43 hectares of land in the Mandai Agrotechnology Park.

name: Singapore Zoo
desc: Come up close and personal with the over 3200 mammals, birds and reptiles and fishes at this 20-hectare "open" zoo.

name: Kranji War Memorial
desc: Honouring the men and women who gave their lives for freedom in WWII.

name: Bollywood Veggies
desc: This organic farm specialises in healthy locally grown produce with no chemical fertilisers, pesticides and growth hormones and also offers heary home-cooked meals at its in-house eatery.

name: Hay Dairies
desc: With about 1000 goats of mixed breeds on the farm, milking seesions take place from 9am to 11am to produce fresh goat's milk for sale. Educational tours available for groups of 10 or more.

name: Dream Fish - Merlion Arowanas Farm
desc: Specialising in breeding Singapore's Merlion Arowana fish, which is also known as the dragon fish. With a total of 116 ponds, it has the largest Arowana breeding farm locally.

name: Nyee Phoe Flower Garden
desc: Revel in the rustic natural landscape of Sungei Buloh at the tranquil flower garden with an extensice nursery to help you create your own lush garden.

name: Aero-green Technology
desc: The first aeroponics farm in Asia to adapt aeroponic technology for the growth of vegetables in Singapore. It aims to provide clean, free and quality vegetables grown through aeroponic technology.

name: Farmart
desc: You'll find a quail farm, a Koi farm, an ornamental fish farm, and live lobsters and crabs. Children will be entertained here as they can feed the many animals like tortoises, goats, fishes and frogs.

name: Chengtai Nursery
desc: Sitting on a block of about 4 acres, the nursery has a wide range of bonsai trees, both for the expert and the bonsai beginner. It's the perfect place to immerse yourself in the world of bonsai.

name: Memories at Ford Factory
desc: View relics, photographs, newspaper clippings and learn more about Singapore's past.

name: Wild Wild Wet
address: Downtown East 1 Pasir Ris Close Singapore 519599
desc: Singapore's biggest water theme park offers high-speed flume rides, a raft slide and an automatic wave pool.

name: Changi Museum
desc: View photographs, drawings and letters created by POWs and civilian internees.

name: Republic of Singapore Air Force Museum
desc: An outdoor gallery with a viewing deck which provides a panoramic view of aviation classics.

name: Chinese Heritage Centre
desc: Promotes understanding of the culture and traditions of Chinese communities overseas through the collection, preservation and display of artwork.

name: Army Museum of Singapore
desc: Journey from the turbulent days of Singapore's pre-independence period to the current-day capabilities of the 2nd Generation Army.

name: Singapore Discovery Centre
desc: Guests will be able to immerse themselves in Singapore's past, present and future, travelling through time to key moments in our nationhood and experiencing them as they happen.

name: Jurong Bird Park
desc: 8000 colourful birds of 600 species will amaze you with their variety, shapes and sizes.

name: Science Centre Singapore
desc: For budding scientists, the world-acclaimed Science Centre Singapore will keep your mind racing with more than 1000 interactive exhibits depicting the wonder and beauty of science.

name: Snow City
desc: Snow in tropical Singapore? No, you're not dreaming! At Snow City, Singapore's first indoor snow centre, you can experience real snow, a sub-zero climate and a three-storey high snow slope!

name: Chinese Garden
desc: A signature architectural building of the Chinese is the pagoda, used in ancient times by Buddhists to keep human bones. The seven-storey pagoda "Ru Yun Ta" follows the style of Pagoda in Nanjing.

name: Dynasties Antique & Art Gallery
desc: Home to over 8000 art pieces from acclaimed local and overseas artists.

name: Sun Yat Sen Nanyang Memorial Hall
desc: This national monument remembers the revoluntionary efforts that toppled the Qing dynastic rule and heralded the start of modern China.

name: New Water Visitor Centre
desc: The NEWater Visitor Centre takes visitors on an exciting journey to learn about Singapore's water story and everything about NEWater through interactive multimedia games and exhibits.

name: Ski 360
desc: Experience waterskiing or wakeboarding where the participants are not pulled by a boat but by an overhead cable, very similar to a snow ski lift, but erected around the banks of a lake.

name: Katong Antique House
desc: Filled with every type of traditional Peranakan costumes, crockery and furniture.

name: Sri Senpaga Vinayagar Temple
desc: Built in the mid-19th century, the Sri Senpaga Vinayagar Temple was re-built in 2003. Some interesting features include the Rajagopuram entrance tower which features the Chola style of architecture.

name: Eurasian Heritage Centre
desc: Located in Katong, The Eurasian Heritage Centre offers fascinating insight into the Eurasian culture.

name: Thekchen Choling
desc: Founded by Singapore-born Lama Thubten Namdrol Dorje in 2001, Thekchen Choling Singapore is a Tibetan Buddhist Temple that emcompasses both the Tibetan & Chinese tradition.

name: Sakya Muni Buddha Gaya Temple
desc: A 15-metre high statue of Buddha, surrounded by a seemingly endless chain of lights, is the focal point of this simple but impressive building.

name: Marina Barrage
desc: The Marina Barrage is a dam built across the Marina Channel forming Singapore's 15th reservoir, and the first in the city.

name: Asia Ancient Gallery
address:
Tanglin Shopping Centre 
19 Tanglin Road 
#03-28 
Singapore 247909
desc: Offering a collection of practical antiques such as dining tables and chairs.

name: Haw Par Villa
desc: Enjoy an amazing world of Chinese folklore, legends and history at Haw Par Villa which houses more than 1000 statues and 150 giant dioramas.

name: Reflections at Bukit Chandu
desc: The exhibits within depict Japanese invasion plans alongside British strategic maps, photographs and documents.

name: Sentosa Island
desc: Just 15 minutes away from the city centre is Sentosa, an idyllic resort island with pristine beaches, world-class attractions, sea sports, golf and retreats.

name: Church of True Light
desc: Set in Little India, the architecture of this Anglican Church reflects strong Chinese influences and the Church's roots.

name: Masjid Abdul Gaffoor Mosque
desc: Tucked away from the bustle of Little India, this mosque was completed in 1910 and recently restored. The main entrance of this mosque boasts an alaborate pediment, the center of which is a sundial.

name: Hajjah Fatimah Mosque
desc: Built in 1846, the Mosque is named after a Malacca-born Malay who married a wealthy Bugis Sultan. Although it exhibits a combination of architectural influences, it has a decidedly British flavour.

name: Malay Heritage Centre
desc: Showcasing Malay culture and heritage in Singapore through historic artefacts, multimedia and dioramas displays and exhibits.

name: Sultan Mosque
desc: With its massive golden dome and huge prayer hall, the Sultan Mosque is one of Singapore's most imposing religious buildings.

name: Sculpture Square
desc: Houses extensive gardens, shaded courtyards and a dramatic nine-metre high pillar-free exhibition hall.

name: Maghain Aboth Synagogue
desc: Singapore's small Jewish community congregates regularly at the Maghain Aboth Synagogue, which conducts regular services and observances of Jewish festivals.

name: St. Joseph's Church
desc: The architectural marvel of the church is structured in the form of a Latin cross and boasts beautifully crafted stained glass windows.

name: 8Q SAM / Singapore Art Museum
desc: Has the largest public collection of modern and contemporary Southeast Asian artworks in the world.

name: MINT Museum of Toys
desc: A world-class toy collection consolidated from more than 25 countries some over 100 years old.

name: National Museum of Singapore
desc: The custodian of Singapore's 11 national treasures including the Singapore Stone.

name: CHIJMES
desc: A Neo-Classical style building which houses one of Singapore's most aesthetically-pleasing dining and entertainment venues.

name: Connoisseur Art Gallery
desc: First established as a non- profit organisation in 1989 to promote and expand the reach of highly-talented Chinese artists.

name: Fort Canning Park
address: Fort Canning Park, 70 River Valley Rd, Singapore 179037
desc: A place of historical importance in Singapore, Fort Canning Park was formerly known as “Forbidden Hill”, and was once the seat of royalty for the Malay rulers in 1300s. It later became a residence for colonial leaders, and was also an important military base during World War II.

name: The Substation
desc: An independent contemporary arts centre.

name: Peranakan Museum
desc: Delve into the rich history, traditions and culture of early settlers in the former Straits Settlements of Singapore, Malacca and Penang.

name: Ngee Ann Cultural Centre
desc: Portrays the culture and traditions of the Teochews through the medium of visual and performing arts.

name: Sri Thandayuthapani Temple
desc: The unique feature of this Southern Indian temple is the roof with 48 engraved glass panels which are angled to catch the rising and setting sun.

name: Singapore Hong San See
desc: Established by the Hokkien people of the Lam Ann clan, this temple is dedicated to Guang Ze Zun Wang, the God of Fortune.

name: Singapore Philatelic Museum
desc: Catch a glimpse of Singapore's heritage through a vast collection of rare stamps and philatelic material.

name: Armenian Church
desc: The Armenian Church in Hill Street is credited with being the oldest church in Singapore. Built in 1835 and designed by colonial architect, George Coleman.

name: St. Andrew's Cathedral
desc: A distinctive and elegant institution in the heart of the civic district designed by Colonel Ronald MacPherson in 1856.

name: Singapore Flyer
desc: Offers you breathtaking, 360 degrees panoramic views of Singapore and beyond. Located at Marina Bay, it sits astride a three-storey Retail Terminal with an exciting array of retail and F&B choices.

name: Civil Defence Heritage Gallery
address: Civil Defence Heritage Gallery, 62 Hill St, Singapore 179367
desc: Traces fire fighting and civil defence developments in Singapore from the late 1800s.

name: 72-13 TheatreWorks
desc: Increase the awareness of human and social issues through quality art, and features regular shows.

name: Singapore Tyler Print Institute
desc: Pushes the technical and aesthetic frontiers of print- and paper-making.

name: Esplanade - Theatres on the Bay
desc: Affectionately known as the durian, it offers a complete lifestyle experience in shopping, dining and the performing arts.

name: Tan Si Chong Su Temple
desc: This ancentral Hokkien temple, which is also a community centre for the Tan clan in Singapre, is said to have excellent feng shui.

name: Aseana Gallery
desc: Opened by curator Ng Kee Yam, an avid art collector with over 35 years in art acquisitions.

name: The Arts House
desc: The only gazetted government building designated as a multi-disciplinary arts centre.

name: Asian Civilisations Museum
desc: Built in 1865, it was a courthouse for 10 years occupying the Registry of Births and Deaths and later, the Immigration Department.

name: Merlion Park
desc: Standing at 8.6 metres high and weighing 70 tonnes, the Merlion statue has a lion's head and a fish's body, and is housed in this 2500 square metre park.

name: Marina Bay Sands
desc: With a luxury hotel, state-of-the art convention and exhibition facilities, theatres, and some of the best shopping and dining in the region, this is the place to go for world-class entertainment.

name: Lau Pa Sat
desc: The largest remaining Victorian filigree cast-iron structure in Southeast Asia is now a favourite food centre of the locals.

name: Jamae Chulia Mosque
desc: Ironically, one of Singapore's most established mosques is located in the heart of Chinatown! Built in 1826 by the Chulias.

name: Chinatown Heritage Centre
desc: Each level of the Centre takes you to a different time in the history of Chinatown and allows you to trace the lives of its early occupants.

name: Sri Mariamman Temple
desc: Singapore's oldest Hindu temple is an impressive structure in Chinatown with a profusion of deities carved all over its walls, bell-decked doors and frescoes on the ceilings.

name: Buddha Tooth Relic Temple
desc: The Temple is a living cultural monument in the heart of Chinatown housing. Buddhist leaders regard the Sacred Buddha Tooth Relic in a magnificient Relic Stupa composed of 420kg of gold.

name: Singapore City Gallery
desc: See the whole of Singapore from a unique vantage point, right under your feet! An exclusive, giant aerial photograph gives you a panoramic view of Singapore without climbing great heights.

name: Red Dot Design Museum
address:
28 Maxwell Road, 
Red Dot Traffic 
Singapore 069120
desc: The museum encompasses everything that is to do with contemporary that is to do with contemporary design and architecture.

name: Galerie Belvedere
address: Old Hill Street Police Station, 140 Hill St, Singapore 179369
desc: Displays Southeast Asian and international contemporary works.

name: Art Facet
desc: Art gallery showcasing artworks from around the world, with a focus on Israeli art.

name: Aryaseni Art Gallery
desc: Showcases the best in Indonesian fine art.

name: NUS Museum
address: University Cultural Centre National University of Singapore 50 Kent Ridge Crescent Singapore 119279
desc: Formerly called the National University of Singapore (NUS) Museums, the NUS Art Museum was established in 1997 on the scenic Kent Ridge campus. It aims to create an enriching experience of the social history and the art of Asia to NUS and the nation through strategic acquisitions, exhibitions and research of an extensive range of artworks.

name: Opera Gallery
address: Ion Art Gallery, 2 Orchard Turn, Singapore 238801
desc: If you're into high end art, this gallery is a must-visit and you can trust that you're buying from the experts. The gallery has been bringing masterpieces of art to Singapore since 1994 and the collection here includes pieces by Picasso, Buffet, Dali, Gauguin, Miro, Braque and Chagall.

name: Art Plural Gallery
desc: It’s a feast for the senses at Art Plural Gallery, Southeast Asia’s largest art gallery devoted to modern, contemporary art and design.

name: HDB Gallery
address: Fusion Bistro HDB Hub, 480 Lorong 6 Toa Payoh, HDB Hub, Singapore 310480
desc: Embark on a 360-degree adventure and witness the transformation of living conditions from the pre-60s slums to the vibrant towns of today.

name: Living Portraits Gallery
address: Raffles Country Club, 450 Jalan Ahmad Ibrahim, Singapore 639932
desc: Explore the transformation of Singapore through this gallery of creative work.

name: Gajah Gallery
desc: Established in 1966, Gajah Gallery explores the diverse socio-cultural interests of Asia through art from Indonesia, Vietnam, India and Singapore.

name: Artfolio
desc: Artfolio is a visual art gallery that was founded in 1990 to increase awareness and appreciation for Southeast Asian art in Singapore.

name: Yang Gallery Pte Ltd
desc: Yang Gallery Singapore brings together the largest collection of contemporary chinese art of any art gallery in Singapore.

name: Ode to Art Contemporary
address:
252, North Bridge Road
Raffles City Shopping Centre, #01-36E/F
Singapore 179109
desc: Ode To Art features an international spectrum of artists, with works such as paintings, sculptures and photography.

name: Chan Hampe Galleries
address: 328 North Bridge Road, #01-04 Raffles Hotel Arcade Singapore 188719
desc: A platform for East-West cultural exchanges, Chan Hampe Galleries is an exciting contemporary art space with a primary focus on Singaporean art.

name: Collectors Contemporary
address: 5 Jalan Kilang Barat #01-03 Petro Centre Singapore 159349
desc: Using entering Collectors Contemporary, you'll be greeted by an elegant and spacious environment of 3000 square feet.

name: Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple
desc: At the heart of Little India on Serangoon Road, the Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple is dedicated to the ferocious Hindu Goddess of power, Kali.

name: Old Hill Street Police Station
desc: The Old Hill Street Police Station was built in 1934 to house the Hill Street Police Station and Barracks. At the time of its completion in 1934, the building was the largest government building and was regarded as a modern skyscraper.

name: Thian Hock Keng Temple
desc: In a place like Singapore, where Chinese immigrants first came in boats, there is bound to be a temple dedicated to Mazu, the Goddess of the Sea.

name: Dalhousie Obelisk
desc: The Dalhousie Obelisk is situated in the Civic District of Singapore and was built to commemorate the second visit of Marquis of Dalhousie in February 1850.

name: The Helix Bridge
desc: Linking Marina Bay to Marina Centre, the Helix Bridge, is set to become Singapore’s next landmark. Located beside the Benjamin Sheares Bridge, alongside the vehicular Bayfront Bridge, it was officially opened on 24 April 2010 and is the world’s first curved bridge.

name: Rumah Bebe
desc: The traditions of Peranakan culture are kept alive at Rumah Bebe, one of the last bastions of their important heritage.

name: Singapore Coins and Notes Museum
desc: Head to Singapore’s first and only museum dedicated to the showcase of currency. See exhibits on coins, notes and items used for barter trade from colonial times to present.

name: YMCA Singapore
desc: The original YMCA building, which was demolished to make way for the current YMCA, was used as a headquarters for the East Branch of the Kempeitai, the much feared Japanese Military Police during the Japanese Occupation of Singapore.

name: Singapore City Hall
desc: City Hall at St Andrew's Road was originally known as the Municipal Building when it was completed in 1929. Renamed in 1951, it housed various government bodies before it became home to the Singapore judiciary in 1987.

name: Labrador Nature Reserve
desc: Explore the rocky cliff-side vegetation and enjoy the panoramic views of the sea at Labrador Nature Reserve. This park is an oasis of calm and a tranquil getaway from the hustle and bustle of the city.

name: Lian Shan Shuang Lin Temple
desc: If you are looking to visit a temple in Singapore, be sure to stop by the famous Lian Shan Shuang Lin Temple in Toa Payoh. Seated on 50 acres of land donated by a devout Buddhist, Low Kim Pong, the genesis of this temple is a story to behold.

name: Central Sikh Temple
desc: Learn more about the life of the Sikhs in Singapore at the Central Sikh Temple. The chief place of worship for Singapore’s 15,000 Sikhs, the Central Sikh Temple was built to commemorate the 518th anniversary of Guru Nanak, the first Sikh guru.

name: Gardens by the Bay
desc: Visit Gardens by the Bay, one of the Top 10 Indoor Gardens of the World, arguably the nation’s most beautiful masterpiece. Moreover, it was recently awarded the 2014 International Thea Awards for Outstanding Achievement - Botanical Garden, by the Themed Entertainment Association.

name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve
desc: Covering an area of approximately 3,043 hectares, Bukit Timah Nature Reserve has been left mostly undisturbed; despite the progress and development that has transformed much of Singapore.

name: Mount Faber
desc: When it comes to planning a romantic or leisurely outing with friends and loved ones, The Jewel Box at Mount Faber Park provides the perfect backdrop. Housing a retail shop, cable car rides and five different restaurants and bar concepts, The Jewel Box offers a holistic yet distinct experience for any occasion.

name: Hort Park
desc: Billed as Singapore’s one-stop gardening hub, Hort Park sits on a lush 23-hectare area. The park connects Kent Ridge Park all the way to Telok Blangah Park, and brings together recreation, education, research, retail and gardening in one setting.

name: MacRitchie Reservoir Park
desc: The MacRitchie Reservoir was constructed in 1867, and currently has boardwalks skirting the edge and walking trails through the forest. They range in distances from 3 km to 11 km.

name: Singapore Botanic Gardens
desc: Awarded the 2013 Travellers’ Choice Attraction by TripAdvisor, the sprawling Singapore Botanic Gardens provides great respite from the hustle and bustle of the city.

name: Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve
desc: Have a unique glimpse of migratory birds as they make their winter journey to the warmer climates of Australia – with some coming from as far away as Siberia in their long journey south.

name: East Coast Park
address: East Coast Park, East Coast Park Service Rd, Singapore 449876
desc: With its beachside location and a host of recreational activities, East Coast Park won’t leave you disappointed. Add that to a wide range of restaurants, bars and cafes – it’s not surprising that the park is one of Singapore’s most popular venues.

name: Pulau Ubin
desc: Go back in time to a simpler life at Pulau Ubin, the last village or “kampong” in Singapore. A visit here is like taking a time warp back to the 1960s when things were much simpler, as you’ll notice from the old wooden houses.

name: Mana Mana
desc: Mana Mana East Coast is a beach club that offers the best options for waterspts regukars and amateurs in Singapore. The centre features a proshop, with a range of waterspots equipment, as well as great dining and bar facilities.

name: Singapore Indoor Stadium
desc: Concert goers and sports fans have thronged this arena since its opening in December 1989. Many sports stars, rockstars and world-famous bands have captivated audiences with performances at the Singapore Indoor Stadium in Kallang.

name: ION Sky
desc: Located on levels 55 and 56 and at an impressive 218 metres, ION Sky is the new focal point of the city. A must-visit destination offering an unrivalled 360-degree view from the highest point on Orchard Road, it houses an observatory, event space, and the Salt grill & sky bar.
